<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> <m>\lap\{af(t)+bg(t)\}</m> </title>

	<p>
		Now that we've explored individual Laplace transforms, let's see how we can combine them using a fundamental property: linearity.
	</p>

	<example>

		<m>\quad</m> Use the definition of the Laplace transform to compute
		
		<me> \lap\{15 + 6e^{7t} - 11t\}. </me>
		
		<solution>
			<p>
				Starting from the definition:
				<md>
					<mrow> 
						\lap\{15\ +\amp\ 6e^{7t} - 11t\}	
					</mrow>
					<mrow>		
							=\amp\ \int_0^{\infty} e^{-st} \cdot \left(15 + 6e^{7t} - 11t\right)\ dt
					</mrow>
					<mrow>
							=\amp\ \int_0^{\infty} \left( 15e^{-st} + 6e^{-st} \cdot e^{7t} - 11e^{-st} \cdot t \right)\ dt
					</mrow>
					<mrow>	
							=\amp\ \int_0^{\infty} 15e^{-st} \cdot 1\ dt + \int_0^{\infty} 6e^{-st} \cdot e^{7t}\ dt + \int_0^{\infty} 11e^{-st} \cdot t\ dt
					</mrow>
					<mrow>	
							=\amp\ 15\int_0^{\infty} e^{-st}\cdot 1\ dt + 6\int_0^{\infty} e^{-st} \cdot e^{7t}\ dt - 11\int_0^{\infty} e^{-st} \cdot t\ dt
					</mrow>
				</md>
				Each of the integrals above correspond to a Laplace transform we've already seen.
				<md>
					<mrow>
						\amp= 15\lap\{1\} + 6\lap\{ e^{7t} \} - 11\lap\{ t \},
					</mrow>
					<mrow>
						\amp= \ub{\frac{15}{s}}_{s \gt 0} + 6\ub{\frac{1}{s - 7}}_{s \gt 7} - 11\ub{\frac{1}{s^2}}_{s \gt 0}.
					</mrow>
				</md>
			</p>
		
			<p>
				To satisfy all the conditions on <m>s</m>, we must have <m>s \gt 7</m> since that ensures all terms are defined. Therefore, 
				<me> \lap\{15 + 6e^{7t} - 11t\} = \frac{15}{s} + 6\cdot \frac{1}{s-7} - \frac{11}{s^2}, \quad s \gt 7. </me>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<p>
		This example illustrates how Laplace transforms inherit some of their properties directly from integrals. In particular, if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constants, then:
		<me> \lap\{ a f(t) \pm b g(t) \} = a \lap\{ f(t) \} \pm b \lap\{ g(t) \}, </me>
	</p>

	<assemblage xml:id="lt-properties-P1"><title>Laplace Transform Property <m>P_1</m></title>
		<p>
			Let <m>F(s) = \lap{f(t)}</m> and <m>G(s) = \lap{g(t)}</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			<dl width="narrow">
				<li xml:id="P1"><title><m>P_1</m></title>
					<m>\ds \lap\{ a f(t) \pm b g(t) \} = a F(s) \pm b G(s), \quad a, b </m> are constants
				</li>
			</dl>
		</p>
	</assemblage>

